WEBVTT

00:15.724 --> 00:21.980
And believe you are
      as graceful as an animal.

00:22.022 --> 00:24.357
And now you are a giraffe!

00:24.399 --> 00:26.943
--Ah!

00:26.985 --> 00:29.779
And now you're a bird!

00:30.572 --> 00:32.532
That's beautiful.

00:33.450 --> 00:36.911
Just flying. Yeah.

00:39.581 --> 00:42.000
And what are we now?
           We're monkeys!

00:47.422 --> 00:51.551
All right.
     Peg is here for story time!

00:51.593 --> 00:54.095
-Yay!
       -Hello, everyone.

00:54.137 --> 00:55.972
Hi, Miss Peg.

00:56.014 --> 00:58.308
Wow, your dancing
        looked so beautiful!

00:58.349 --> 01:00.018
Thank you!

01:00.060 --> 01:02.395
-You guys have fun?
               -Yeah!

01:02.437 --> 01:05.899
Great. All right.
     Well, now it is story time.

01:05.940 --> 01:08.735
Before we get to our story,
 I wanted to tell you about my...

01:08.777 --> 01:11.237
-Say, that was pretty swell.
       -No spectators allowed.

01:11.279 --> 01:13.740
upbeat ragtime music plays

01:18.078 --> 01:19.913
Betty! Wait.

01:19.954 --> 01:22.916
If you come to my class,
         you have to dance.

01:22.957 --> 01:24.084
Next week, then.

01:24.125 --> 01:25.502
You can teach me
          how to be a bird.

01:26.878 --> 01:28.922
I don't know
     if you have what it takes.

01:29.631 --> 01:31.091
You might be surprised.

01:31.132 --> 01:33.176
I'm pretty good
         on the dance floor.

01:34.886 --> 01:36.596
Peg wanted me to meet you.

01:36.638 --> 01:38.723
Thought this was the only place
        I could pin you down.

01:38.765 --> 01:40.642
Oh, and you thought
       you could pin me down?

01:40.683 --> 01:42.769
It's Gerald. Gerald Ford.

01:42.811 --> 01:44.604
I'd have to live
        in a cave to not know

01:44.646 --> 01:47.398
the football star of South High
         and the Wolverines.

01:47.440 --> 01:48.983
Well, in Peg's defense,

01:49.025 --> 01:50.610
I've been putting pressure
         on her to set me up

01:50.652 --> 01:52.362
since I got back
          from the Pacific.

01:55.824 --> 01:59.953
So, what do you say?
      Will you go out with me?

02:01.579 --> 02:02.997
Should I invite my husband?

02:25.353 --> 02:26.729
Hello?

02:28.189 --> 02:29.315
Betty?

02:32.152 --> 02:34.154
-Betty?
               -Bill.

02:35.363 --> 02:36.489
Betty.

02:37.866 --> 02:40.994
-Bill? Bill, shh. It's okay.
               -Betty.

02:41.870 --> 02:43.872
-It's okay.
          -Where were you?

02:45.331 --> 02:46.374
Where were you?

02:47.667 --> 02:48.918
Bill, are you awake?

02:53.173 --> 02:55.175
I haven't been anywhere, Bill.

02:56.342 --> 02:58.136
Betty.

02:58.178 --> 02:59.637
You've been in a coma.
            You need to--

02:59.679 --> 03:00.722
Betty.

03:03.933 --> 03:05.018
Betty.

03:05.643 --> 03:06.811
Bill?

03:55.318 --> 03:57.445
This land is your land

03:59.906 --> 04:02.700
This land is my land

04:05.703 --> 04:09.082
From California

04:09.123 --> 04:14.003
To the New York island

04:14.045 --> 04:18.132
From the redwood forest

04:19.676 --> 04:21.427
To the Gulf Stream waters

04:24.681 --> 04:26.266
I tell you

04:26.307 --> 04:28.851
This land

04:28.893 --> 04:33.815
Was made for you and me
                 Yeah

04:39.404 --> 04:43.449
One bright sunny morning

04:43.491 --> 04:48.371
In the shadow of the steeple

04:48.413 --> 04:53.209
Down by the welfare office

04:53.251 --> 04:58.339
I saw my people

04:58.381 --> 05:00.675
I was wondering

05:00.717 --> 05:03.177
If this land

05:03.219 --> 05:08.099
Was made for you and me

05:16.024 --> 05:17.150
Morning.

05:19.402 --> 05:22.572
It's good to see you
    looking so much better, Bill.

05:22.613 --> 05:25.491
Here is some crispy bacon,
        just how you like it.

05:26.701 --> 05:28.244
What's the hurry?

05:28.286 --> 05:30.246
Oh, I'm just going
     to be late for work, Bill.

05:30.288 --> 05:33.458
Well, why don't you lie down
      next to me for a minute?

05:33.499 --> 05:35.168
What about your breakfast?

05:35.209 --> 05:37.670
I don't want breakfast.
             I want you.

05:37.712 --> 05:39.672
Well, your mother's
            going to be--

05:39.714 --> 05:40.840
Just fucking take it!

05:40.882 --> 05:43.384
Goddamn it! Take it!

05:45.845 --> 05:48.097
I want my wife
       to lie down next to me.

05:49.057 --> 05:50.558
Is that too much to ask?

05:52.226 --> 05:53.519
No.

05:56.147 --> 05:58.149
Soon enough,
        I'm gonna be better,

05:58.191 --> 05:59.692
and you won't have to work.

05:59.734 --> 06:04.072
And you get to stay home
         like a normal wife!

06:04.113 --> 06:05.490
Good morning.

06:08.409 --> 06:09.619
Good morning.

06:16.542 --> 06:19.754
He was a famous trumpet man
         from out Chicago way

06:19.796 --> 06:22.715
He had a boogie style
     that no one else could play

06:22.757 --> 06:25.176
He was the top man
             at his craft

06:25.218 --> 06:26.719
But then his number came up

06:26.761 --> 06:28.596
And he was gone
            with the draft

06:28.638 --> 06:31.015
He's in the army now
          a blowin' reveille

06:31.057 --> 06:34.185
He's the boogie woogie
        bugle boy of Company B

06:34.227 --> 06:37.188
They made him blow a bugle
          for his Uncle Sam

06:37.230 --> 06:40.483
It really brought him down
      because he couldn't jam...

06:40.525 --> 06:42.360
And two, sweetheart.

06:42.402 --> 06:45.238
-Can I get an ashtray?
   -Look what the cat dragged in.

06:45.279 --> 06:46.864
This sure is
        off the beaten path.

06:46.906 --> 06:48.574
Well, wouldn't want anyone
           to see you out

06:48.616 --> 06:51.244
with a married woman.
         People might talk.

06:59.252 --> 07:00.420
You look nice.

07:02.672 --> 07:03.756
Just nice?

07:08.636 --> 07:10.012
You look beautiful, Betty.

07:11.764 --> 07:14.016
And you look very well,
          yourself, Jerry.

07:17.645 --> 07:19.147
What have you been doing lately?

07:20.982 --> 07:22.233
Thinking about you.

07:31.909 --> 07:33.911
You ever dream, Betty?

07:33.953 --> 07:36.664
You know,
     getting to quit your jobs?

07:37.498 --> 07:38.916
Why would I want to do that?

07:40.293 --> 07:42.795
I-- I happen to like working.

07:44.005 --> 07:45.506
Don't you dream, Betty Bloomer?

07:45.548 --> 07:48.968
Warren. Betty Warren.

07:49.010 --> 07:50.136
Right.

07:54.015 --> 07:58.311
And, um-- And yet it hasn't
    stopped you from calling me.

08:00.938 --> 08:03.107
Peg, you know,
       she told me about him.

08:06.402 --> 08:08.905
Yeah, she told me about Bill.

08:12.742 --> 08:15.077
My mother disapproved, so...

08:17.997 --> 08:21.334
That's all it took.
       We-- We got married...

08:25.671 --> 08:27.798
And it didn't take me long
        to realize that home

08:27.840 --> 08:31.010
was the only thing
      we had in common, and...

08:32.678 --> 08:34.055
and having a good time.

08:35.014 --> 08:37.725
But Bill's good time means...

08:40.603 --> 08:42.438
having breath as hot as whiskey

08:42.480 --> 08:44.941
when he's screaming
         right in your face

08:44.982 --> 08:48.736
and, um, punching holes
    in the walls of our bedroom.

08:59.413 --> 09:01.290
I'm sorry,
   you don't want to hear about--

09:01.332 --> 09:03.042
I want to hear everything.

09:09.590 --> 09:11.384
I was planning on leaving him.

09:12.885 --> 09:16.180
I was working on it and then
    he fell into a diabetic coma.

09:18.683 --> 09:20.685
You can't leave a man in a coma.

09:22.687 --> 09:25.064
The behavior you're describing
         is against the law.

09:26.190 --> 09:27.233
The law?

09:28.234 --> 09:29.485
I'm a lawyer.

09:30.987 --> 09:32.446
That's abuse.

09:35.616 --> 09:38.411
Well, you don't know
      anything about me, Jerry.

09:50.548 --> 09:52.717
People... 

09:52.758 --> 09:54.844
People will talk, Mr. Ford.

09:54.885 --> 09:57.597
upbeat jazz music playing

10:09.150 --> 10:11.360
You know her,
        she's always on time.

10:11.402 --> 10:14.614
You know how she is about
    being on time for everything.

10:18.909 --> 10:20.286
Hey, can you honk?

10:23.122 --> 10:24.457
-Oh.
               -Yeah?

10:26.167 --> 10:28.419
--Yeah, yeah.

10:34.133 --> 10:38.137
Hey, Mama!

10:38.179 --> 10:42.933
Hey, hey! Is that my little girl
    back from Harvard Law School?

10:42.975 --> 10:45.978
-Oh, hey, Daddy.
                -Hey.

10:48.022 --> 10:50.733
-Look at you.
          -No, look at you.

10:52.318 --> 10:54.320
Oh, I missed you.

11:11.212 --> 11:13.422
That was good. What were you
    scrunching up your face for?

11:13.464 --> 11:15.883
That was right. 

11:17.134 --> 11:19.095
-Yeah. Yeah.
               -Yeah?

11:23.724 --> 11:26.185
See, now you lost it.
          Now you lost it.

11:28.062 --> 11:30.272
You'd better go back to the top.

11:30.314 --> 11:32.066
Oh, oh.

11:33.693 --> 11:36.112
I got your favorite.
            Spinach dip.

11:36.153 --> 11:37.697
-Hey.
                -Oh!

11:37.738 --> 11:40.366
-Listen to that.
        -Mmm. I'm listening.

11:40.408 --> 11:43.119
Yeah, I'm sure Roberta Flack

11:43.160 --> 11:44.787
played it just like that.

11:56.590 --> 11:58.676
So, are you ever gonna tell us
           about the meeting

11:58.718 --> 11:59.885
they flew you in for?

11:59.927 --> 12:01.512
First class.

12:01.554 --> 12:03.931
-She fancy now.
               -Yeah.

12:03.973 --> 12:06.016
-How'd it go?
            -It was good.

12:06.058 --> 12:10.771
Yeah. Sidley Austin, huh?
     That's a big-time law firm.

12:10.813 --> 12:14.150
-Yeah, one of the biggest.

12:14.191 --> 12:16.277
So, uh, you still rockin'

12:16.318 --> 12:18.904
-those old slippers, huh, Daddy?
     -You know it. That's right.

12:18.946 --> 12:21.240
That man ain't never
       gonna get rid of them,

12:21.282 --> 12:23.492
even though they do stink
           to high heaven.

12:23.534 --> 12:27.413
Ha! Just like I always say,
      "Use it up. Wear it out."

12:27.455 --> 12:29.540
"Make it do,
           or do without."

12:29.582 --> 12:31.125
That's right.

12:35.129 --> 12:38.966
So, uh,
      how long have you been...

12:40.259 --> 12:42.678
Oh, well, uh, two weeks.

12:42.720 --> 12:44.513
It took Medicare a bit,

12:44.555 --> 12:46.348
but they finally
         got me this chair.

12:46.390 --> 12:48.601
Wish they would get him
          a motorized one,

12:48.642 --> 12:52.104
but that old hunk of metal
     is all they would pay for.

12:52.146 --> 12:55.775
Well, I'll be making money
             in no time,

12:55.816 --> 12:58.110
so I can get you
   whatever chair you need, Daddy.

12:58.152 --> 13:00.780
Uh-uh, uh-uh. I'm not taking
     any of my daughter's check.

13:00.821 --> 13:02.156
Daddy, let me do this.

13:03.157 --> 13:04.158
Hmm.

13:05.659 --> 13:08.287
Been hardheaded
     since you were in the womb.

13:08.329 --> 13:11.081
Matter of fact,
     I've still got the bruises.

13:15.085 --> 13:17.129
pensive music

13:30.851 --> 13:32.228
Sorry, he's still not here.

13:32.937 --> 13:34.271
Lord.

13:34.313 --> 13:36.273
I hate it
    when people aren't punctual,

13:36.315 --> 13:38.567
especially on their first day.

13:38.609 --> 13:40.820
I'm also mad it's the brother
        that's gotta be late.

13:40.861 --> 13:43.739
You know? I mean, come on now.
        You gotta represent.

13:43.781 --> 13:46.158
-Mm-hmm. 
         -Thanks, Lorraine.

13:46.200 --> 13:47.326
Mm-hmm.

13:48.202 --> 13:50.079
-Oh.
            -Hey. Sorry.

13:50.120 --> 13:52.373
-Come on in, Mr. Obama.
             -Thank you.

13:54.124 --> 13:58.045
Hi, uh, I'm Barack.
 Um, my apologies for being late.

13:58.087 --> 14:00.339
Start with these.

14:02.091 --> 14:04.051
-Okay.
     -Uh, we'll need all of that

14:04.093 --> 14:05.636
back by tomorrow.

14:05.678 --> 14:08.305
And, uh, Lorraine can show you
            to your desk.

14:09.348 --> 14:12.059
Okay. Thanks.

14:15.145 --> 14:17.147
-Nice to meet you.
              -Mm-hmm.

14:28.450 --> 14:30.578
Thought I'd get
         some fresh air too.

14:30.619 --> 14:33.706
Uh... mind if I, uh, join you?

14:34.540 --> 14:37.501
Uh, sure. 

14:37.543 --> 14:41.714
I have, uh, two muffins,
          if you want one.

14:43.007 --> 14:44.466
Thanks.

14:45.926 --> 14:49.388
Do you always eat
    breakfast pastries for lunch?

14:49.430 --> 14:52.850
Uh, it's fun to
       switch it up sometimes.

14:52.892 --> 14:56.896
Mmm.
   Well, I eat a salad every day.

15:02.860 --> 15:05.321
I gotta say. You're, uh--

15:05.362 --> 15:08.240
You're a lot more laid-back
      than I imagined you'd be.

15:08.282 --> 15:10.159
-Oh, yeah?
               -Yeah.

15:10.200 --> 15:12.369
The partners made it sound
    like I was gonna be mentoring

15:12.411 --> 15:13.871
the next Thurgood Marshall.

15:13.913 --> 15:15.080
Oh.

15:16.790 --> 15:20.544
Hardly. Just
   the light-skinned lawyer part.

15:22.796 --> 15:25.633
Honestly,
    I think my success at Harvard

15:25.674 --> 15:30.387
has been because I really took
     my time before I got there.

15:30.429 --> 15:32.640
Reading too many books
           for my own good

15:32.681 --> 15:35.935
and organizing here in Chicago.

15:36.644 --> 15:38.145
Oh. Is that right?

15:39.939 --> 15:43.609
Yeah, uh-- South Side, mostly.

15:43.651 --> 15:45.778
That's where I grew up.

15:45.819 --> 15:47.905
Yeah,
   that's where all my people are.

15:47.947 --> 15:49.365
That's...

15:50.616 --> 15:55.287
I envy that.
 I'm actually, uh, writing a book

15:55.329 --> 15:57.790
about my search for identity

15:57.831 --> 15:59.625
and not knowing
        a lot of my family--

15:59.667 --> 16:02.252
Hold up. You're writing a book?

16:05.547 --> 16:07.800
Yeah.
   That probably sounds so, um---

16:07.841 --> 16:08.926
Pretentious?

16:11.303 --> 16:15.307
But, you know, also impressive.

16:19.937 --> 16:21.480
I'll take that as a compliment.

16:22.856 --> 16:25.943
-I mean, okay.

16:33.742 --> 16:38.205
Hey. So I hope you don't mind if
 I duck out a little early today.

16:38.247 --> 16:40.457
Meaning you hope I don't mind
      you asking my permission

16:40.499 --> 16:42.209
to duck out a little early?

16:42.251 --> 16:44.253
Yep.
    That's exactly what I meant.

16:44.294 --> 16:47.506
Wow. My man's
     only been here a few weeks

16:47.548 --> 16:49.967
and already he's slacking off.

16:50.009 --> 16:52.928
I'm sorry. Did you not read
      the 30-page memo I wrote

16:52.970 --> 16:56.015
on corporate governance that all
   the partners are raving about?

16:56.056 --> 16:58.517
-I'm making you look good.
              -Mm-hmm.

17:03.313 --> 17:06.567
Boy. If you don't get those
   broke-ass shoes off my couch...

17:06.608 --> 17:09.695
And you might be impressing
        all the partners here

17:09.737 --> 17:11.989
who are dazzled by any Black man
         with a vocabulary,

17:12.031 --> 17:13.824
but remember,
         I'm the one writing

17:13.866 --> 17:17.036
your end-of-summer review
    and I know Negroes like you.

17:21.540 --> 17:25.544
Um, so you know,
   the reason I wanna leave early

17:25.586 --> 17:28.464
is to help out
 one of my old organizer friends.

17:28.505 --> 17:31.717
It's actually over by
           where you live.

17:33.052 --> 17:34.511
On Euclid, right?

17:36.346 --> 17:37.931
What, are you stalking me?

17:37.973 --> 17:39.767
No. 

17:39.808 --> 17:45.439
I listen closely,
       intently, passionately.

17:45.481 --> 17:48.859
You're so full of shit.

17:48.901 --> 17:50.736
Come out.
      We never get to hang out.

17:50.778 --> 17:56.033
Besides, it'll be fun.
     And it's for a good cause.

17:56.992 --> 17:58.827
I don't know.

17:58.869 --> 18:01.538
I mean, in fact, after
   red-lining all these contracts,

18:01.580 --> 18:04.583
all I want is a glass of Zin
           and a footbath.

18:04.625 --> 18:08.962
I get that. It's just, I've been
 cooped up in Cambridge all year.

18:09.004 --> 18:11.924
It'd be nice to connect
           with real folks

18:11.965 --> 18:14.259
whose circumstances
       could be so much better

18:14.301 --> 18:17.846
if they only knew
   how much power they would have

18:17.888 --> 18:19.515
if they lobbied together.

18:19.556 --> 18:22.392
And no one ever wants
         to tell them that.

18:27.689 --> 18:31.610
Well, good luck with that,
        Half-Black Superman.

18:31.652 --> 18:34.738
Um, I will see you

18:34.780 --> 18:37.825
bright and early
       tomorrow morning, 45.

18:39.159 --> 18:40.244
Get outta here.

18:41.787 --> 18:43.789
You're the best boss in Chicago.

18:52.714 --> 18:56.510
You can have influence
            in this city.

18:56.552 --> 18:58.554
You can make change.

19:00.264 --> 19:03.433
But it means listening
          to your neighbor,

19:03.475 --> 19:05.477
trusting your neighbor.

19:06.436 --> 19:09.731
It means joining this coalition.

19:13.152 --> 19:14.069
Hey.

19:14.570 --> 19:16.280
Hi. Sorry.

19:16.321 --> 19:18.240
-Glad you could make it.
               -Yeah.

19:18.949 --> 19:20.075
Hello, everyone.

19:20.117 --> 19:21.368
-Hello.
                -Hi.

19:21.410 --> 19:22.786
-How are you?
            -Who is she?

19:23.537 --> 19:25.080
Uh, it's my boss.

19:25.122 --> 19:27.666
That's what
   they're calling it these days?

19:31.003 --> 19:33.380
Out of my league
        is what they call it.

19:37.176 --> 19:39.636
I know what you're thinking.

19:39.678 --> 19:42.764
"Who are these
        kids coming in here,

19:42.806 --> 19:45.225
telling us what we want?

19:45.267 --> 19:47.269
With their big old ears.
            Forget 'em."

19:50.606 --> 19:55.652
But trust me,
     these kids have heard you.

19:55.694 --> 19:59.072
We know you spend your days
            on the phone

19:59.114 --> 20:01.408
fighting with
       these big corporations.

20:01.450 --> 20:03.202
Asking them for medical care

20:03.243 --> 20:06.205
that should not be a privilege,
            but a right.

20:06.246 --> 20:08.665
You shouldn't have to fight
           to be healthy.

20:08.707 --> 20:11.627
And we can change that.
              Together.

20:11.668 --> 20:14.838
And not take no for an answer
             because...

20:14.880 --> 20:17.299
do we wanna settle
       for the world as it is,

20:17.341 --> 20:21.345
or do we fight for the world
          as it should be?

20:21.386 --> 20:23.388
-Yeah!

20:23.430 --> 20:25.390
dramatic music

21:13.272 --> 21:14.564
Ah.

21:19.111 --> 21:20.153
Jane.

21:36.003 --> 21:37.713
Eloise. Elizabeth.

21:40.966 --> 21:42.759
That is Madame Souvestre.

21:42.801 --> 21:46.305
She's the most interesting
     person you will ever meet.

21:46.346 --> 21:48.807
I thought we were only
      supposed to speak French.

21:48.849 --> 21:52.102
Yes, but you don't
       speak French very well.

21:52.144 --> 21:53.645
What makes you say that?

21:53.687 --> 21:55.814
You didn't say anything
          that whole time.

21:55.856 --> 21:59.401
So, either you struggle
     with French or you're shy.

22:05.157 --> 22:07.701
If Madame Souvestre
    thinks we'll be fast friends,

22:07.743 --> 22:10.954
then so we shall.
         She's always right.

22:12.914 --> 22:13.874
Come.

22:37.564 --> 22:38.690
Jane?

23:07.469 --> 23:08.970
I'm sure beauty

23:09.012 --> 23:10.764
is what gives
     your life meaning, Abigail.

23:10.806 --> 23:13.266
But not all of us
         have what you have.

23:17.312 --> 23:22.651
Abigail is a young woman
       with a keen intellect.

23:22.692 --> 23:26.446
-Just like you are, Eleanor.
                -Yes.

23:26.488 --> 23:29.157
But I am not beautiful
            like Abigail.

23:29.199 --> 23:30.617
According to whom?

23:31.576 --> 23:32.744
My mother.

23:37.541 --> 23:40.460
And was she an expert
           on the subject?

23:44.297 --> 23:48.176
She was disappointed and ashamed
     to have such a plain child.

23:50.262 --> 23:54.933
It sounds like your mother
    may have been the plain one.

23:57.811 --> 24:02.399
Ladies. Can we agree
       that the idea of beauty

24:02.441 --> 24:07.487
is far more complex than the way
     someone's face is arranged?

24:07.529 --> 24:12.367
The color of her eyes,
        her hair, her smile.

24:12.409 --> 24:16.079
These things may make
       an initial impression,

24:16.121 --> 24:19.916
but it is when
        we cultivate our mind

24:19.958 --> 24:23.295
that our true beauty
            is revealed.

24:24.337 --> 24:27.132
The very act of thinking,
            questioning,

24:28.133 --> 24:31.428
learning, being curious--

24:31.470 --> 24:36.141
that is where
       our true beauty exists.

24:37.184 --> 24:40.145
pensive music

24:43.190 --> 24:46.485
-No, I don't believe it.
        -It's true, I swear.

24:46.526 --> 24:48.987
I was sent here because
   he was sick with embarrassment.

24:50.363 --> 24:53.283
Describe exactly what you
    saw when you opened the door.

24:53.325 --> 24:56.578
And say it slowly
      so we can all picture it.

24:56.620 --> 24:59.623
Well, I was in my room
       and it was quite late.

24:59.664 --> 25:01.416
And I heard Mama
          moaning in pain.

25:01.458 --> 25:03.877
I thought she was ill. Or worse.

25:06.254 --> 25:09.007
I walked upstairs...

25:10.050 --> 25:12.010
And I listened
         right by the door.

25:12.052 --> 25:15.180
She was crying,
   and father was making a noise,

25:15.222 --> 25:18.141
-almost like a farm animal.

25:18.183 --> 25:19.809
So, I pried the door open

25:19.851 --> 25:23.104
and I saw them on the bed,
            stark naked.

25:23.146 --> 25:25.440
-What?
     -Father was on top of Mama.

25:25.482 --> 25:28.068
And it seemed like he might
     crush her with his weight.

25:28.109 --> 25:31.071
And then he suddenly cried out.

25:33.782 --> 25:35.367
What?

25:35.408 --> 25:38.370
So I shrieked.
     And that's how they saw me.

25:40.497 --> 25:42.874
-That sounds so frightening.
            -Yes.

25:42.916 --> 25:45.377
But it can't be like that
      for every woman, though.

25:45.418 --> 25:47.712
Perhaps Emma's father
          is a cruel sort.

25:47.754 --> 25:50.215
Well, I'd like to ask
          Madame Souvestre,

25:50.257 --> 25:51.800
to get a definitive answer.

25:52.759 --> 25:55.220
-She wouldn't know.
              -Why not?

25:55.262 --> 25:57.639
I'm quite sure
         she is a sapphist.

26:04.938 --> 26:06.606
What does that mean?

26:06.648 --> 26:09.317
She only has relations
          with other women.

26:10.610 --> 26:12.445
At least a woman
       wouldn't weigh so much.

26:29.838 --> 26:34.301
Graceful. Graceful.
       Great. Better, better.

26:34.342 --> 26:37.012
All right. That's beautiful.

26:37.053 --> 26:39.431
Remember, we--
       Everyone in the store,

26:39.472 --> 26:41.975
they want to be us.
      Or they want to marry us.

26:42.017 --> 26:45.979
Great job. Great job. All right.
     Let's do it one more time.

26:49.107 --> 26:50.609
Burning the midnight oil,
               Howard?

26:51.776 --> 26:53.612
I still haven't heard
      on the buyer job, Betty.

26:56.323 --> 26:58.700
Well, sales the last two months
     have been the highest ever.

26:58.742 --> 27:01.119
And they've only been going up
       since I started working

27:01.161 --> 27:02.704
-with the girls.
               -Betty.

27:02.746 --> 27:04.789
I couldn't have sung
      your praises any louder.

27:04.831 --> 27:08.460
I'm sure the job is yours.
   I'll let you know when I know.

27:09.210 --> 27:10.295
Okay.

27:11.504 --> 27:12.589
Good night.

27:16.092 --> 27:18.386
We both know that
    this marriage isn't working.

27:22.891 --> 27:24.643
A petition for divorce?

27:25.769 --> 27:27.604
And all you have to do is sign.

27:31.941 --> 27:34.694
You know I'm not paying you
             a red cent.

27:35.820 --> 27:38.323
I wouldn't dream
          of asking you to.

27:38.365 --> 27:41.660
Now, who do you think is
    gonna want a divorced woman?

27:41.701 --> 27:44.037
You're gonna end up alone.

27:47.874 --> 27:49.751
Well, that's a chance
         I'll have to take.

27:49.793 --> 27:52.671
dramatic music

28:02.138 --> 28:06.101
I, uh-- I wouldn't have
      taken you for a cone guy.

28:06.142 --> 28:09.229
Always. They're better
        for the environment.

28:09.270 --> 28:11.606
-And you know what else?
               -What?

28:11.648 --> 28:16.486
It's a container you can eat!
         How great is that?

28:18.029 --> 28:21.241
You're such a giant geek.
        You know that, right?

28:21.282 --> 28:23.284
Yeah, I'm fully aware.

28:27.288 --> 28:31.042
Uh, I'm really glad
      you came the other night.

28:31.084 --> 28:33.086
Mmm, me too.

28:34.087 --> 28:36.047
You were great up there.

28:37.507 --> 28:40.885
You really, um--
        Believe in all of it?

28:41.511 --> 28:42.721
Politics?

28:45.223 --> 28:48.476
So much in our lives
            is political.

28:48.518 --> 28:52.397
Education, health, employment.

28:52.439 --> 28:54.566
This park. Everything.

28:54.607 --> 28:57.193
Is your ice cream political?

28:57.235 --> 28:59.612
Does your
    environmentally friendly cone

28:59.654 --> 29:02.907
make you a liberal
     and my cup a conservative?

29:02.949 --> 29:04.784
Hey, you said it.

29:04.826 --> 29:07.245
Oh, fool, please.

29:09.330 --> 29:12.208
I don't know.
    Politics is just not for me.

29:13.001 --> 29:15.044
And public speaking?

29:15.086 --> 29:17.630
You know, I flunked
     my last exam in high school

29:17.672 --> 29:19.758
so I didn't have to give
       the valedictory speech.

29:19.799 --> 29:21.509
-Come on.
           -No, seriously.

29:22.302 --> 29:24.345
The performance of it, ah...

29:28.516 --> 29:30.393
So, um...

29:31.686 --> 29:36.191
one of those ladies asked if,
        uh, you were my girl.

29:37.192 --> 29:39.152
I'm nobody's girl.

29:40.195 --> 29:41.154
Woman.

29:42.906 --> 29:44.532
You're ridiculous.

29:44.574 --> 29:46.618
You are incandescent.

29:49.829 --> 29:51.164
I want to see you more.

29:54.667 --> 29:55.710
Hmm.

29:59.172 --> 30:01.466
Oh, look. It's gonna rain.
         Don't you love it?

30:02.008 --> 30:03.718
Uh, no.

30:03.760 --> 30:06.387
What, is that what
    those Harvard white girls do?

30:06.429 --> 30:08.640
You know, this hair, rain,
            it don't mix.

30:08.681 --> 30:10.183
I'm parked right over there.

30:12.310 --> 30:14.562
-Come on. Hurry.

30:14.604 --> 30:16.606
All right. Hurry.
      I got the door. Hold on.

30:16.648 --> 30:19.400
-Oh! Go, go, go, go, go!
   -All right. You got it? Get in.

30:19.442 --> 30:21.653
Whoo! 

30:23.196 --> 30:24.989
God, I'm soaked.

30:26.533 --> 30:28.243
Oh, God.

30:34.499 --> 30:37.168
I didn't know you were driving
       Fred Flintstone's car.

30:37.210 --> 30:39.504
Doesn't that scare
        the shit out of you?

30:39.546 --> 30:43.675
Nah, it keeps me grounded.
   I can literally see the ground.

30:43.716 --> 30:47.011
Oh, really? What, you give
     that line to all the girls?

30:47.053 --> 30:50.974
Yeah, I get so many girls
        in this beat-up thing

30:51.015 --> 30:52.892
-that they're just lining up.

30:52.934 --> 30:54.227
Believe me.

30:58.731 --> 31:03.027
So, uh, what's your end goal?

31:04.737 --> 31:06.698
Making partner?

31:06.739 --> 31:09.284
Uh, opening up
         your own practice?

31:09.325 --> 31:11.452
Get a car with a floor?

31:11.494 --> 31:15.623
--Uh, end goal? Um...

31:15.665 --> 31:17.542
Yeah. What kind of---

31:19.085 --> 31:21.129
sentimental music

31:53.286 --> 31:54.954
Well, uh... Whoo.

32:34.118 --> 32:38.122
Yes, hello. Is Mr. Ford
      available by any chance?

32:38.164 --> 32:40.458
This is... This is Betty.

32:40.500 --> 32:43.044
I'm sorry, ma'am.
         He's gone for the day.

32:53.137 --> 32:57.433
Grab your coat
           and get your hat

32:57.475 --> 33:02.063
Leave your worry
           on the doorstep

33:02.105 --> 33:06.025
Just direct your feet

33:06.067 --> 33:10.571
To the sunny side
            of the street

33:10.613 --> 33:14.826
Can't you hear a pitter-pat?

33:14.867 --> 33:17.537
And that happy tune
           is your step...

33:17.578 --> 33:20.248
Hi. This is Betty Bloomer
        calling for Mr. Ford.

33:20.289 --> 33:21.874
Just one minute.

33:26.963 --> 33:28.131
This is Jerry.

33:28.172 --> 33:30.174
Hi. Hi. This is Betty.

33:30.216 --> 33:31.801
Is-- Is now a good time?

33:31.843 --> 33:33.761
Hey, Betty. I'm actually
      kinda swamped right now.

33:33.803 --> 33:35.221
Can I call you back
          in a little bit?

33:36.723 --> 33:39.350
Yes. Yes, of course.
       Of course, that's fine.

33:39.392 --> 33:41.519
Well, great. Talk to you soon.

33:44.230 --> 33:49.110
I used to walk in the shade

33:49.152 --> 33:53.656
With those blues on parade

33:53.698 --> 33:57.285
Well, since you asked me,
      this one is my favorite.

33:57.326 --> 33:59.162
Have you seen
        these cluster pearls?

33:59.203 --> 34:01.164
Yes, I have.
        Have you seen these?

34:03.750 --> 34:06.002
Hello.
      Ford and Buchen Law Office.

34:06.044 --> 34:10.131
Hi, yeah, uh, is Mr. Ford there?
         It's Betty Bloomer.

34:10.173 --> 34:12.425
I'm sorry. He's not here.

34:12.467 --> 34:15.178
-Are you sure?
            -Yes, I'm sure.

34:18.723 --> 34:21.309
-Hey. I got it!
                -Wow!

34:21.350 --> 34:23.686
-I can't believe it!
      -Congratulations, Eugene.

34:23.728 --> 34:25.605
-Thank you. Thank you.
                -Wow!

34:28.775 --> 34:30.359
Eugene got
       the buyers job, Howard?

34:30.401 --> 34:32.820
Give me a second, Marty.

34:32.862 --> 34:34.655
Betty, this came
       from way above my head.

34:34.697 --> 34:37.283
You couldn't have sung
       my praises any louder?

34:37.325 --> 34:39.827
-Was that even true?
           -Yeah. Mostly.

34:39.869 --> 34:41.537
Mostly?

34:41.579 --> 34:45.041
Ah... Marty. Yeah,
 I'm gonna have to call you back.

34:45.083 --> 34:47.085
Look.

34:47.126 --> 34:49.253
You're a young woman.

34:49.295 --> 34:52.840
The second I give you this job,
       you start having kids.

34:52.882 --> 34:55.885
Taking weekends and months off.

34:55.927 --> 34:58.096
Then we realize we probably
          should have hired

34:58.137 --> 34:59.597
someone else in the first place.

35:01.933 --> 35:04.227
Well, I could have done
          this job pregnant

35:04.268 --> 35:07.563
since you're doing it sitting
      on that fat ass of yours.

35:15.154 --> 35:16.989
Not only did I make the mistake

35:17.031 --> 35:18.574
of listening to your advice,

35:18.616 --> 35:20.493
I stupidly believed you

35:20.535 --> 35:23.079
when you said you were going
          to be there for me.

35:23.121 --> 35:25.915
I'm guessing you only said
      those things for one reason.

35:29.460 --> 35:31.170
Well, congratulations.

35:31.212 --> 35:34.215
You're like every other man
               out there.

35:34.257 --> 35:38.094
I hope you're pleased
      with yourself, Mr. Jerry...

35:40.763 --> 35:43.432
"Thinks he's God's gift" Ford.

35:47.937 --> 35:49.981
-Yes.
    -And when the new collections

35:50.022 --> 35:52.817
are gonna start,
     then we have to get ready.

35:54.694 --> 35:56.821
Okay,
    so I think we should get here

35:56.863 --> 36:00.032
at 00 a.m. tomorrow,
     and then will you lock up?

36:00.074 --> 36:02.660
-All right. Good night, guys.
         -Good night, Betty!

36:04.537 --> 36:05.454
Betty.

36:06.789 --> 36:09.750
I... I received your letter.

36:13.337 --> 36:14.505
So, I...

36:15.673 --> 36:18.092
I just-- I wanted
    to tell you how sorry I was.

36:23.097 --> 36:26.517
I tried calling you.
           Where were you?

36:27.685 --> 36:30.021
Sometimes with work,
        I just get so focused

36:30.062 --> 36:32.315
and days go by, you know?

36:32.356 --> 36:36.569
I... In this case,
        it was too many days.

36:37.862 --> 36:39.030
I'm sorry.

36:40.656 --> 36:41.991
Look, I...

36:43.659 --> 36:46.037
Look, I've never met
          a woman like you.

36:48.497 --> 36:50.041
Okay? I don't wanna lose you.

36:51.209 --> 36:53.002
Will you give me
       another chance, Betty?

36:54.170 --> 36:55.880
Just give me one more shot.

37:01.636 --> 37:02.720
Maybe.

37:05.056 --> 37:06.515
You have to call me.

37:07.308 --> 37:08.726
Yeah, I will.

37:10.353 --> 37:12.313
I'll call you every night
           if you let me.

37:14.190 --> 37:15.566
Every afternoon too.

37:19.153 --> 37:20.488
I'm gonna go call you right now.

37:20.529 --> 37:22.823
"Beguin The Beguine" playing

37:29.205 --> 37:30.790
Hello.

37:30.831 --> 37:33.084
Yes, hello.
   May I please speak with Betty?

37:36.295 --> 37:38.214
That depends. Who's calling?

37:38.256 --> 37:40.258
This is her future husband.

37:42.593 --> 37:44.470
Um, I'm sorry.

37:44.512 --> 37:47.098
Betty is unavailable
           at the moment.

37:54.563 --> 37:57.525
So what do you want to do today?
   Go to the park or get married?

37:57.566 --> 37:59.151
I'm kinda on the fence.

38:00.569 --> 38:02.029
Definitely the park.

38:02.947 --> 38:04.073
You sure?

38:06.575 --> 38:09.787
Have fun at work.
         Talk to you later.

38:29.181 --> 38:30.641
--Hello?

38:32.393 --> 38:34.645
-Betty?
               -Jerry?

38:37.982 --> 38:39.150
I'm in here.

38:42.903 --> 38:45.114
Hi. Are those for me?

38:45.156 --> 38:46.198
Maybe.

38:49.827 --> 38:51.495
Could I convince you
          to come join me?

38:53.331 --> 38:57.001
I don't know.
    Men don't take baths, Betty.

38:59.378 --> 39:00.921
Too bad for men.

39:08.137 --> 39:10.681
-You're not gonna fit.
   -Too late. Hey, I'm getting in.

39:13.976 --> 39:15.102
What a mess!

39:16.062 --> 39:17.813
Hey, you invited me.

39:24.070 --> 39:27.156
So, you know that question
     that you've been asking me.

39:28.366 --> 39:30.201
The one about getting married?

39:32.912 --> 39:33.996
Yeah.

39:37.666 --> 39:41.003
I'd love to become
       your wife, Jerry Ford.

39:44.131 --> 39:45.424
Yeah?

39:54.392 --> 39:56.435
"Begin the Beguine" playing

40:11.242 --> 40:15.246
Now, honey,
       there's no use fussing.

40:17.540 --> 40:19.333
Daddy, this is ridiculous.

40:19.375 --> 40:21.085
We've been here
        for over three hours,

40:21.127 --> 40:23.879
and I've seen people get called
      in who got here after us.

40:23.921 --> 40:25.673
Welcome to hospitals.

40:27.550 --> 40:29.260
I'm going to
        see what's going on.

40:32.430 --> 40:35.433
Excuse me,
    you see my father over there?

40:35.474 --> 40:38.602
He's clearly in a lot of pain
   and this is an emergency room.

40:38.644 --> 40:40.521
And I'm wondering why
     there's no sense of urgency

40:40.563 --> 40:42.440
in getting him treated
       as quickly as possible?

40:42.481 --> 40:44.525
As you can see, a lot of people
        are in the same boat.

40:44.567 --> 40:46.360
He'll be seen when his name
       is called. Be patient.

40:46.402 --> 40:49.822
Okay, look. I understand
       how waiting rooms work.

40:49.864 --> 40:52.408
What I don't get is why folks
        who got here after us

40:52.450 --> 40:54.285
are getting seen before him.

40:55.035 --> 40:56.370
Depends on your insurance.

40:58.205 --> 40:59.623
Fucking HMO.

41:00.749 --> 41:04.670
Okay. Okay. Fine.

41:04.712 --> 41:07.548
How much will it cost to get
       my dad seen right now?

41:07.590 --> 41:10.092
Give me a number.
   I may not look like it to you,

41:10.134 --> 41:12.052
but I actually
        make a lot of money.

41:12.094 --> 41:14.305
That's not how it works.

41:14.346 --> 41:16.474
It's all right,
        sweetie. I can wait.

41:16.515 --> 41:20.478
Come sit next to your dad.

41:50.049 --> 41:51.091
Hey.

41:53.552 --> 41:58.390
Chicken Parmesan from Spiaggia
           for... milady.

41:58.432 --> 42:00.392
Thank you.

42:03.270 --> 42:04.355
What's wrong, baby?

42:08.609 --> 42:10.569
It's my dad.

42:10.611 --> 42:14.240
They, uh, want to keep him
       in the hospital longer.

42:14.281 --> 42:17.785
Oh, Mich... Oh, I'm sorry.

42:17.826 --> 42:22.706
I just... Ugh, I can't.

42:22.748 --> 42:25.709
Shit. I just didn't
        really think anything

42:25.751 --> 42:27.378
could ever stop
         my daddy, you know?

42:28.337 --> 42:31.340
I'm sorry.

42:31.382 --> 42:33.384
Yeah, I don't know
           what we'll do.

42:36.262 --> 42:38.055
He's a remarkable man,

42:38.097 --> 42:42.726
and he raised a brave,
        remarkable daughter.

42:44.061 --> 42:46.230
Well, he doesn't think
       you're half bad either.

42:51.610 --> 42:53.487
Yeah, I don't think
       I'm really brave enough

42:53.529 --> 42:56.574
to see him like this, you know?

42:59.493 --> 43:02.955
You are the hardest-loving
           person I know.

43:02.997 --> 43:04.999
I mean, that's why I, uh...

43:05.040 --> 43:08.794
I know that you're... the one.

43:15.843 --> 43:20.055
You mean... the one?

43:20.097 --> 43:22.474
Yeah, I'm sorry. I didn't mean
       to make it about that.

43:22.516 --> 43:23.601
But that's, uh...

43:25.102 --> 43:27.062
that's just how I feel, though.

43:35.446 --> 43:36.488
Me too.

44:06.518 --> 44:09.480
The president
     shall be with you shortly.

44:15.444 --> 44:17.696
-Uncle Teddy.
           -There she is.

44:17.738 --> 44:20.866
Ah. Let me take a look at you.

44:22.660 --> 44:25.871
Why, you're all grown up, Nel!

44:28.123 --> 44:29.750
Only you call me that.

44:29.792 --> 44:31.043
Please.

44:34.088 --> 44:35.631
-Thank you.
             -Thank you.

44:39.093 --> 44:42.304
I was ordered home
           by Grandmother

44:42.346 --> 44:45.349
to attend this inane
          coming out party.

44:45.391 --> 44:48.185
-Ah, yes, your debut.
                -Yes.

44:48.227 --> 44:51.772
My education was cruelly
       cut short for a dance.

44:53.816 --> 44:55.859
I read that you dined
     with Booker T. Washington.

44:55.901 --> 44:57.444
Mm-hmm.

44:57.486 --> 44:59.446
What was it like
   to have dinner with such a man?

44:59.488 --> 45:01.699
It was just like dining
          with anyone else.

45:02.783 --> 45:04.827
-Ah. Thank you.
       -Thank you.

45:06.745 --> 45:09.832
So, Nel, what do you plan to do

45:09.873 --> 45:13.460
with this fine partial education
          you've received?

45:13.502 --> 45:16.088
Help those who are
           less fortunate.

45:16.130 --> 45:17.798
Those who don't have the luxury

45:17.840 --> 45:20.008
of Allenswood to introduce them
            to the world.

45:20.050 --> 45:23.387
Seems this Madame Souvestre
   has made quite the impression.

45:23.429 --> 45:26.223
Oh. Yes.

45:26.265 --> 45:29.518
And to answer your question,

45:29.560 --> 45:31.729
what I plan to do is teach,

45:31.770 --> 45:33.772
and what I plan not to do

45:33.814 --> 45:36.191
is participate
        in this absurd ritual

45:36.233 --> 45:37.901
of putting on a frilly dress

45:37.943 --> 45:41.280
to try to attract
         a suitable husband.

45:41.321 --> 45:45.159
So, you'll become a brilliant,
       accomplished spinster.

45:45.200 --> 45:46.660
No children, no family.

45:46.702 --> 45:48.412
Madame Souvestre
       doesn't have a husband,

45:48.454 --> 45:50.080
and look what
        she has accomplished.

45:50.122 --> 45:51.248
Hmm.

45:54.710 --> 45:57.963
Life is about relationships.

46:00.215 --> 46:02.676
Not just romantic ones,
     but all sorts of alliances

46:02.718 --> 46:04.428
that can help us along the way.

46:06.513 --> 46:08.766
You never know who you may meet

46:08.807 --> 46:11.101
at even the dreariest
            of functions.

46:12.394 --> 46:15.898
So I say put on the dress
               and go.

46:19.485 --> 46:21.945
-Is that your advice?
                -Mmm.

46:27.075 --> 46:31.413
At the very least, it'll give
    you something to write about.

46:31.455 --> 46:34.792
Your letters show great promise.

46:51.183 --> 46:53.101
-Luke. Good to see you.
             -Oh, hello.

46:53.727 --> 46:54.812
Eleanor.

46:55.854 --> 46:56.730
One second.

46:58.816 --> 46:59.983
Franklin.

47:01.443 --> 47:02.778
Roosevelt.

47:02.820 --> 47:04.488
Ah!

47:07.825 --> 47:09.660
Wait. 

47:09.701 --> 47:11.954
You were the terrible cousin

47:11.995 --> 47:14.581
who used to carry me around
         when I was little,

47:14.623 --> 47:17.251
and I didn't-- I didn't like it.

47:18.335 --> 47:21.255
-Terrible fifth cousin.
                -Yes.

47:22.589 --> 47:23.966
You don't like dancing?

47:24.007 --> 47:26.718
Oh, I don't like
          mindless rituals

47:26.760 --> 47:28.345
that force a girl to be
            at the whims

47:28.387 --> 47:30.180
of young men she barely knows.

47:30.222 --> 47:32.599
Oh, I'm sure you know
     more people than you think.

47:32.641 --> 47:36.937
Well, I've been studying abroad
          for three years.

47:36.979 --> 47:38.021
I see.

47:39.398 --> 47:41.316
Why did you come, then?

47:43.277 --> 47:45.028
My uncle thought I should.

47:45.070 --> 47:48.866
Your uncle...
      Theodore, the president?

47:49.700 --> 47:50.826
Yes.

47:51.785 --> 47:54.288
Hmm. Sorry, I didn't realize

47:54.329 --> 47:57.332
he had time to weigh in
          on such matters.

47:57.374 --> 48:00.752
Oh, the president chooses
      his time very carefully.

48:04.798 --> 48:06.341
What have you got so far?

48:07.509 --> 48:09.595
Oh.

48:09.636 --> 48:12.639
I don't let anyone read my work
        until it's finished.

48:12.681 --> 48:16.101
Hmm. You know,
       I dabble a bit myself.

48:16.143 --> 48:18.145
I write for   The Harvard Crimson.

48:18.186 --> 48:20.564
Oh! What do you cover?

48:21.398 --> 48:23.108
Whatever they'll print.

48:23.150 --> 48:26.361
In fact, one time,
     I covered your uncle Teddy.

48:26.403 --> 48:30.908
I'm told I may even have a shot
     at editor next year, so...

48:30.949 --> 48:33.744
Franklin, come on,
        the party's upstairs.

48:35.954 --> 48:36.872
So...

48:51.762 --> 48:54.932
We both know I'm too plain
         for you, Franklin.

48:57.225 --> 48:58.560
On the contrary.

48:59.853 --> 49:03.774
I think it's quite clear
   you are the opposite of plain.

49:03.815 --> 49:06.526
In fact, I'm certain you are
       the least plain person

49:06.568 --> 49:08.862
at this entire event.

49:10.197 --> 49:13.909
Maybe the least plain person
        that I have ever met.

49:17.579 --> 49:19.915
The only worry I have

49:19.957 --> 49:22.709
is that I may be
         too plain for you.

49:25.337 --> 49:28.715
So, what do you say?

49:29.216 --> 49:30.592
One dance.

49:36.181 --> 49:37.391
No, thank you.

49:43.647 --> 49:44.690
Okay.

50:16.471 --> 50:18.473
I may need a few minutes.

50:18.515 --> 50:20.600
Uh, that mac and cheese
           was the truth.

50:20.642 --> 50:25.480
Ah. Well, wait till
       you try the pie. Pecan.

50:25.522 --> 50:26.815
My dad's favorite.

50:26.857 --> 50:28.692
He just could not
         stay away from it.

50:28.734 --> 50:31.528
Might need
    you to save me a piece, Mom.

50:31.570 --> 50:33.989
-Aw.
            -I love you.

50:34.031 --> 50:35.824
-Love you too.
    -I'll see y'all later, okay?

50:35.866 --> 50:38.368
Bye, Craig.
      Tell Janis I said hello.

50:38.410 --> 50:40.203
-Yeah, will do.
         -Mm-hmm.

50:46.043 --> 50:47.335
Let me help you with that,
               Marian.

50:47.377 --> 50:48.545
Oh, thank you.

50:50.213 --> 50:52.591
No, no, no, no.
         I'll help your mom.

50:52.632 --> 50:55.761
Give you a chance to, uh,
       finish your case prep.

50:55.802 --> 50:58.889
Okay. Look
    at this gentleman over here.

51:12.819 --> 51:17.240
Um, we've been talking a lot
        about future things.

51:17.991 --> 51:19.910
Oh. Okay.

51:21.870 --> 51:23.413
So, uh...

51:25.791 --> 51:28.460
You think, since
    I've made it this long, uh...

51:31.713 --> 51:34.091
You think, uh, she'd marry me?

51:36.051 --> 51:37.427
Young man...

51:38.804 --> 51:41.598
are you asking me for
   my daughter's hand in marriage

51:41.640 --> 51:44.267
-right here and now?
          -I suppose I am.

51:44.309 --> 51:47.813
I mean, I thought I'd
       at least run it by you.

51:50.482 --> 51:54.861
If Fraser were still here...

51:56.655 --> 52:00.158
he'd know better than to answer
   anything on behalf of Michelle,

52:00.200 --> 52:01.910
and I'm no dummy either.

52:06.706 --> 52:08.625
You're gonna have
        to ask her yourself.

52:09.876 --> 52:11.169
Okay.

52:12.879 --> 52:15.507
Now? No.

52:27.185 --> 52:28.270
Okay.

52:29.604 --> 52:31.648
sentimental music

52:37.529 --> 52:41.658
Ah, beautiful.
        Absolutely beautiful.

52:45.537 --> 52:47.372
Your father would be so proud.

52:48.290 --> 52:50.417
I wish he was here to see this.

52:53.461 --> 52:55.005
My dear Eleanor,

52:56.047 --> 52:58.258
no other success in life,

52:58.300 --> 53:00.719
not the presidency
          or anything else,

53:00.760 --> 53:04.639
compares with the love
       between a man and wife.

53:04.681 --> 53:09.436
Now, I believe you and Franklin
    love each other unselfishly,

53:09.477 --> 53:13.481
and I know good fortune
        will attend you both.

53:15.275 --> 53:16.693
You're a good girl.

53:23.116 --> 53:24.201
Shall we?

53:36.338 --> 53:38.590
You're allowed
         to breathe, Betty.

53:41.760 --> 53:43.803
I don't know why I'm so nervous.

53:43.845 --> 53:45.805
Maybe it's because
         your future husband

53:45.847 --> 53:48.642
felt the need to work
   on the morning of his wedding.

53:48.683 --> 53:51.978
Jerry Ford.
         He's going places.

54:00.028 --> 54:03.698
He's here.
 He's here, he's here, he's here.

54:10.789 --> 54:13.250
Mom, you look beautiful.

54:17.420 --> 54:18.713
Hey.

54:22.259 --> 54:26.096
Oh, Craig, you're wearing
         Dad's old bow tie.

54:26.137 --> 54:28.098
"Use it up, wear it out."

54:28.139 --> 54:29.808
"Make it do, or do without."

54:37.649 --> 54:40.318
Mmm. I'm so proud of you.

54:40.360 --> 54:42.153
-Thank you.
             -Shall we?

54:43.947 --> 54:44.948
Yes.

54:47.951 --> 54:49.953
Oh, yeah, baby

54:51.413 --> 54:54.874
Like a fool
      I went and stayed too long

54:54.916 --> 54:58.878
Now I'm wondering
     if your love's still strong

54:58.920 --> 55:02.090
Ooh, baby, here I am

55:02.132 --> 55:05.051
Signed, sealed, delivered
               I'm yours

55:08.972 --> 55:12.934
Then that time I went
           and said goodbye

55:12.976 --> 55:16.521
Now I'm back
        and not ashamed to cry

55:16.563 --> 55:19.607
Ooh, baby, here I am

55:19.649 --> 55:22.986
Signed, sealed, delivered
               I'm yours

55:25.155 --> 55:27.741
Here I am, baby

55:27.782 --> 55:31.369
Oh, you got my future
            in your hands

55:33.872 --> 55:36.916
Here I am, baby

55:36.958 --> 55:41.338
